reviews.review_text: Comes A Time....for perfection What can I say?  Mr. Seamons has worked his magic again and produced a stellar example of what a matrix should be.  Balance and clarity and a perfect mix.  Add on to that a monster of a show and you can't help but give this one 5 stars.  Hell, the Comes A Time alone gets 10.  One of the best versions I've heard.  Amazing.  This entire show is a fantastic picture of a band firing on all cylinders.  Second set is about as good as it gets.  Crank this one and prepare for liftoff.

Very Entertaining Overall a fun show that has a very passionate acoustic set and a good finish. Would have liked to heard a longer fire and terrapin and less playin in the band but that is just me. I am falling in love with each matrix i hear. So well done and mixed beautifully. Hooray for taking the time!

Beautiful Mix Nice show.  Nice matrix with the board's vocals not being overly dominant.  Jerry Moore's 6-8th row audience position is a critical component of this warm and fuzzy evening.  In some respects, the AUD is good enough to listen to without having to be matrixed.  But the little added extra clarity of the board is the key to this mixed effort.  It really is a beautiful mix.  Highly recommended.

never understood the hype of 5/08 I never have really understood why so many people consider that the HOLY GRAIL of Grateful Dead shows!! There entire spring tour of 77 is amazing. I can say as a Deadhead who missed Jerry by 7 years because I was only born in 1987 but saw my first show "Dead" related show Phil and Friends in 2001 or 2002, that I never listen to 5/8/77. TO me.. the shows leading up to it and after it are the hot stuff... like this show im only up to TLEO and im blown away!

AYEYAYAYAYAYAYAAAAA!!!! NYC-area shows from this time period seem to bring out aggressive audiences.  There's quite a bit of yelling requests at the band between each song.  Additionally, there is some strange guy yelling out "AYEYAYAYAYAYAYAYAYAYAAAA!!!" throughout the entire Palladium run, as well as the Capitol Theatre runs in 1977 and 1976.  Who is this guy and how did he get access to tickets for so many small venue shows?

Other than that, this matrix sounds dynamite.  Hunter Seamons and Charlie Miller deserve statues in the Grateful Dead themepark.

Fantastic This is an absolutely fantastic show that has largely been forgotten among the excellent 1977 shows.

The band knocks just about every track out of the park.  The first set is simply excellent, the Scarlet -> Fire is criminally underrated, and this is one of the best Terrapin Station tracks I've yet heard.

Comes a Time is unfortunately kind of a let-down in the middle of an up-tempo Playing, but that's just a little quibble.  There are also some tonal issues in Dancing; however, Keith's fiddling right at the very end of the track makes it all worth it.

Overall, a very good show.  Worth a second listen – or more.

Love this show and love Hunter's trix I listened to this show countless times on a Maxell XL-IIS or was it an MX-90 "metal" tape.  I have just completely fallen in love with this scar-fire and no other version has ever topped this for me. Jerry's vocals are so vulnerable (especially on comes a time) and his guitar playing is just ferocious.  Plus each jam is just so good.  I am going to listen to more of 5/3/77 since Dave Lemieux released it recently on "Dave's Picks."  To respond to another commenter on this thread, I think the general concensus around 5/8/77 was that a very good soundboard tape of this show was widely circulated when there were not as many other tapes from this spring tour of the same sonic quality. So that is why Cornell just became so revered.  Its also a great show IMO but so many other shows in this run were great too.
